SIMPLE: wassail
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wassail
<hw>Was"sail</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>wes
h⟦amac⟧l</ets> (or an equivalent form in another dialect) be in health,
which was the form of drinking a health. The form <ets>wes</ets> is
imperative. See <er>Was</er>, and <er>Whole</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An ancient expression of good wishes on a festive
occasion, especially in drinking to some one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Geoffrey of Monmouth relates, on the authority of Walter Calenius,
that this lady [Rowena], the daughter of Hengist, knelt down on the
approach of the king, and, presenting him with a cup of wine, exclaimed,
Lord king <qex>waes heil</qex>, that is, literally, Health be to
you.</q> <rj><qau>N. Drake.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An occasion on which such good wishes are expressed
in drinking; a drinking bout; a carouse.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In merry
<xex>wassail</xex> he . . . peals his loud song.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king doth wake to-night and takes his rouse,⟦br⟧
Keeps <qex>wassail</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The victors abandoned themselves to feasting and
<qex>wassail</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The liquor used for a wassail; esp., a beverage
formerly much used in England at Christmas and other festivals, made of
ale (or wine) flavored with spices, sugar, toast, roasted apples, etc.;
-- called also <altname>lamb's wool</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A jolly wassail bowl,⟦br⟧
A <qex>wassail</qex> of good ale.</q> <rj><qau>Old Song.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A festive or drinking song or glee.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you done your <qex>wassail</qex>! 'T is a handsome, drowsy
ditty, I'll assure you.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wassail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wassail
<hw>Was"sail</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to wassail, or to
a wassail; convivial; <as>as, a <ex>wassail</ex> bowl</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A<xex>wassail</xex> candle, my lord, all tallow.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wassail bowl</b></col>, <cd>a bowl in which wassail was
mixed, and placed upon the table.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Spiced <xex>wassail
bowl</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>J. Fletcher.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧When the cloth was
removed, the butler brought in a huge silver vessel . . . Its appearance
was hailed with acclamation, being the <xex>wassail bowl</xex> so
renowned in Christmas festivity.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>W. Irving.</au> --
<col><b>Wassail cup</b></col>, <cd>a cup from which wassail was
drunk.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wassail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wassail
<hw>Was"sail</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To hold a wassail; to
carouse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spending all the day, and good part of the night, in dancing,
caroling, and <qex>wassailing</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wassailer</ent>⟦br⟧
